{{Infobox language |name = Arawak |nativename = Lokono |states = [[French Guiana]], [[Guyana]], [[Suriname]], [[Venezuela]] |region = [[Guianas]] |ethnicity= [[Lokono]] (Arawak) |speakers = 2,510 |date=1990–2011 |ref=e18 |familycolor = American |fam1 = [[Arawakan]] |fam2 = Northern |fam3 = [[Ta-Arawakan]] |iso2 = arw |iso3 = arw |glotto=araw1276 |glottorefname=Lokono }} '''Arawak''' (Arowak/Aruák), also known as '''Lokono''' ('''Lokono Dian''', literally 'people's talk' by its speakers), is an [[Arawakan language]] spoken by the [[Lokono]] (Arawak) people of [[South America]] in eastern [[Venezuela]], [[Guyana]], [[Suriname]], and [[French Guiana]].<ref>Pet, Willem J. A. A Grammar Sketch and Lexicon of Arawak (Lokono Dian). SIL International. 2011. p 2. http://www-01.sil.org/silepubs/Pubs/928474543236/e-Books_30_Pet_Arawak_Suriname.pdf</ref> It is the eponymous language of the Arawakan language family.
Lokono has an [[active–stative]] syntax.<ref>Aikhenvald, "Arawak", in Dixon & Aikhenvald, eds., ''The Amazonian Languages'', 1999.</ref>
== History == Lokono is a critically endangered language.<ref name=":02">{{Cite web|url=http://www.endangeredlanguages.com/lang/1708|title=Lokono|last=|first=|date=|website=endangeredlanguages|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> The Lokono language is most commonly spoken in South America. Some specific countries where this language is spoken include Guyana, Suriname, French Guiana, and Venezuela.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=sPGe7aBSkpkC&oi=fnd&pg=PA167&dq=arawak+language+(lokono)&ots=YVkULFBY7-&sig=1ndPkjAzTIaQwBkqJonmHLWlHnY#v=onepage&q=arawak%20language%20(lokono)&f=false|title=Areal Diffusion, Genetic Inheritance and Problems of Subgrouping: A north Arawak Case Study|last=Aikhenvald|first=Alexandra|date=|website=Google Books|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> The percentage of living fluent speakers with active knowledge of the language is estimated to be 5% of the ethnic population.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Edwards|first=W.|year=1979|title=An Ethnohistory of Amerindians in Guyana|jstor=481091|journal=Ethnohistory|volume= 26| issue = 2|pages=161–175}}</ref> There are small communities of semi-speakers who have varying degrees of comprehension and fluency in Lokono that keep the language alive..<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harbert|first=Wayne|last2=Pet|first2=Willem|date=1988-10-01|title=Movement and Adjunct Morphology in Arawak and Other Languages|url=http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/466095|journal=International Journal of American Linguistics|volume=54|issue=4|pages=416–435|doi=10.1086/466095|issn=0020-7071}}</ref> It is estimated that there are around 2,500 remaining speakers (including fluent and semi-fluent speakers).<ref name=":4">{{Cite journal|last=Aikhenvald|first=Alexandrs|date=|year=2013|title=Arawak Languages|url=https://researchonline.jcu.edu.au/28542/|journal=Aronoff, Mark, (ed.) Linguistics: Oxford Bibliographies. Oxford Bibliographies Online|volume=|pages=|via=Oxford Bibliographies}}</ref> The decline in the use of Lokono as a language of communication is due to its lack of transmission from older speakers to the next generation. The language is not being passed to young children, as they are taught to speak the official languages of their countries. The oldest generation of speakers are around the age of 70 years of age of older.<ref name=":02" />
== Classification == The Lokono language is part of the larger Arawakan language family spoken by indigenous people in South and Central America along with the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-05-01|title=The diachrony of person-number marking in the Lokono-Wayuunaiki subgroup of the Arawak family: reconstruction, sound change and analogy|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0388000116000115|journal=Language Sciences|volume=55|pages=1–15|doi=10.1016/j.langsci.2016.02.001|issn=0388-0001}}</ref> It spans four countries of Central America — Belize, Honduras, Guatemala, Nicaragua — and eight of South America — Bolivia, Guyana, French Guiana, Surinam, Venezuela, Colombia, Peru, Brazil (and also formerly Argentina and Paraguay). With about 40 extant languages, it is the largest language family in Latin America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://research.jcu.edu.au/lcrc/language-archives/south-america-languages/arawak-languages/arawak-languages|title=Arawak languages|website=Research@JCU|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref>
=== Etymology ===
''Arawak'' is a tribal name in reference to the main crop food, the cassava root. It is commonly known as ''Manioc.'' The cassava root is a popular staple to millions in South America, Asia and Africa.<ref name=":8">{{Cite journal|last=Aikhenvald|first=Alexandra|year=2008|title=PERSON MARKING AND DISCOURSE IN NORTH ARAWAK LANGUAGES|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/wol1/doi/10.1111/j.1467-9582.1995.tb00469.x/abstract|journal=Studia Linguistica|volume=49|pages=152–195|via=Wiley}}</ref> It is a woody shrub grown in tropical or subtropical regions. The speakers of the Arawak language also identify themselves as, ''Lokono'', which translates to "the people" . The Arawak language within itself is known as, ''Lokono Dian'', "the people's speech".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Brief_Introduction_to_Some_Aspects_of.html?id=Aq8PAQAAMAAJ|title=A Brief Introduction to Some Aspects of the Culture and Language of the Guyana Arawak (Lokono) Tribe|date=1980|publisher=Amerindian Languages Project, University of Guyana|language=en}}</ref>
=== Alternative Names ===
Alternative names of the same language include Arawák, Arahuaco, Aruak, Arowak, Arawac, Araguaco, Aruaqui, Arwuak, Arrowukas, Arahuacos, Locono, and Luccumi.<ref name=":102">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=A9JSYzAynBEC&oi=fnd&pg=PP2&dq=arawak+language+(lokono)&ots=O3Cqd8O6Xg&sig=Z1nv5BWJ6ivWUiOAI4eLbwAmvto#v=onepage&q=arawak%20language%20(lokono)&f=false|title=Comparative Arawakan Histories : Rethinking Language Family and Culture Area in Amazonia|last=Hill|first=Johnathon|date=|website=Google Books|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
== Geographic Distribution == Lokono is an Arawakan language most commonly found to be spoken in eastern Venezuela, Guyana, Suriname and French Guiana. It was also formerly spoken on Caribbean islands such as Barbados and other neighboring countries. There are approximately 2,500 native speakers today. The following are regions where Arawak has been found spoken by native speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/arw|title=Arawak on Ethnologue|last=|first=|date=|website=Ethnologue|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
