{{Infobox language |name=Isanzu |nativename=''Kinyihanzu'' |states=[[Tanzania]] |ethnicity=[[Isanzu people|Anyihanzu]] |speakers=26,000 |date=2009 |ref =<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/isn|title=Isanzu|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en}}</ref> |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=[[Northeast Bantu]] |fam7=Takama |fam8=[[Iramba language|Iramba]]? |iso3=isn |glotto=isan1243 |glottorefname=Isanzu |guthrie=F.31B }} {{infobox ethnonym | |Anyihanzu |Kinyihanzu |Ihanzu |Isanzu }}
'''Isanzu''' is a [[Bantu language]] of spoken by the [[Isanzu people]] south of [[Lake Eyasi]] in [[Tanzania]].
The position of Isanzu within the Bantu family is uncertain. It is rather distinct in certain features from other Bantu languages of the area, such as [[Turu language|Nyaturu]], but is quite close in others. One easily recognizable feature is /h/ in words where neighboring languages have /s/ or /tʃ/, as in the name Isanzu ~ ''Ihanzu'', a feature it shares with [[Iramba language|Iramba]], and a reason it is commonly classified with Iramba.
