{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}} {{Infobox writer | name = Seymur Baycan | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1976|4|22}} | birth_place = [[Füzuli]], [[Azerbaijan]] | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = journalist and writer | language = | education = Department of Public Administration | alma_mater = [[Qafqaz University]] | period = 2000 – present | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = Quqark (novel) | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | awards = Media Key | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = | portaldisp = }}
'''Seymur Baycan''' ({{lang-az|Seymur Baycan, Seymur XXX}}) – an [[Azerbaijan]]i writer, publicist, columnist.
== Life ==
Seymur Baycan was born in 1976, in [[Fizuli]], Azerbaijan. He graduated from the military school named after [[Jamshid Nakhchivanski]]. He went on to study at [[Qafqaz University]], Department of Public Administration. He left his education and started his literary career. His short stories have been published in Russian, [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] and [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]] languages. He created the ''novel-skeleton'' in world literature. His best-known works include ''18.6&nbsp;cm'', ''Meat and meat products'' and ''Gugark''. In different years he published essays and columns in newspapers ''Milli yol'', ''Reyting'', ''Daily Azerbaijan'', etc. He participated in several regional projects and delivered lectures on cultural topics. Seymur Baycan was awarded with ''Media Key'' for his essay ''The Sunday in Paradise''. He won the writing competition organized by ''Elmar Huseynov Foundation''.
